Association Rules in DOTA 2 Hero Drafting

Association Rules in DOTA 2

Background and Data Import

After manipulation in Python, the imported csv contains approx 100,000 teams (99,930) from 50,000 matches, each with 5 heroes in each team

Mining Association Rules

Mining associations with Apriori results in 5,290 association rules
The parameters have been set to be very low, so as to capture as many association rules as possible, even for less popular heroes
The most significant rules will visible graphically, where the significance of a rule in this context will be determined by the support and lift.
The support is the probability of itemset occuring together.
The lift is the value of the interaction between itemset A and B, i.e. the factor of enhanced response. It is the increased rate of picking itemset B after itemset A compared to the independent probability of picking itemset B

# performing with a very low support to caputre many rules  
# suppot of 0.001 translates to approx 100 games out of 99,930
# confidence of 0.025 translates to the probability of itemset B appearing, given that itemset A has appeared, is 2.5%
# minlength of items transates to the rule containing at least 2 items
dota_rules <- apriori(transactions_dota, parameter = list(support =
                          0.001, confidence = 0.025, minlen = 2))

# sorting DOTA rules by lift, and displaying first 10 rules
dota_rules <- sort(dota_rules, by="lift")
inspect(dota_rules[1:10])

We can see that 622 rules are redundant (less predictive than a more general rule)

# finding and removing any redundant rules
# A rule is redundant if a more general rules with the same or a higher confidence exists, as it would be equally or less predictive than a more general rule. A rule is more general if it has the same RHS but one or more items removed from the LHS. Formally, a rule X -> Y is redundant if
# for some X' subset X, conf(X' -> Y) >= conf(X -> Y).
print(sum(is.redundant(dota_rules)))
[1] 622
inspect(dota_rules[is.redundant(dota_rules)])
## removing any redundant rules
dota_rules <- dota_rules[!is.redundant(dota_rules)]
inspect(dota_rules)

Analysis of Association Rules

All Rules

Plotting 50 highest lift rules with arulesViz results in a somewhat difficult to read graph

plot(dota_rules[1:50], method="graph")

Gephi provides a much more flexible visualisation tool * Support = Node Size * Lift = Colour, where a bolder green indicates a higher lift

Association rules can be visualised close to the corresponding heroes, note the directional nature of the associations. Without any experience playing the game, perceived associations could now be investigated. More experienced players could infer the reasons for the associations; some have been explained below

Rules associated with 1 Hero

Here we will look at rules associated with 1 hero - Legion Commander

# finding subsets of rules containing Legion Commander
legion_rules <- subset(dota_rules, items %in% "Legion Commander")
inspect(legion_rules)

We can see the top 10 rules by Lift

inspect(legion_rules[1:10])

Sizing nodes by support and colouring nodes by lift, we can see a very high lift for skywrath mage, and a high lift with tinker, storm spirit and sniper.
These rules appear to be reciprocal in direction, i.e. a player is as likely to recognise an opportunity to pick skywrath after seeing a legion commander pick, as a player is to recognise an opportunity to pick legion commander after a skywrath pick. This would not necessarily be the case if players who play legion commander, tend to place more value the combo more than skywrath players.

We can also see a high support in rules that contain pudge or invoker, and a fairly high lift. The support statistic alone does not provide much insight, since the heroes invoker and pudge are popular anyway, but together with a fairly high lift, this translates to these heroes being expected to be seen at an even higher rate when paried with legion commander, than in an average game.

Some perceived hero associations might be very hard to infer, and may involve map positioning, farm priority, early game effectiveness and many other factors, however the most common associations with Legion Commander are fairly well known. Legion Commander’s “Duel” ability, allows her to fight an opponent in a fixed position for a lengthy period of time, providing a long disable in a small area. Heroes that can provide enormous damage in a small area of effect, which can otherwise be hard to excecute due to an enemies movement, benefit greatly from Legion Commander’s “Duel” ability. Skywrath mage’s “Mystic Flare”, Storm Spirit’s “Ball Lightning” and Invoker’s “Sun Strike” are all prime examples of this.

Top 50 rules containing Legion Commander by Lift

Rules containing 3 Heroes

This section contains a brief analysis of association rules involving 3 heroes

# Subsetting rules containing 3 items
# rules_2_items <- subset(dota_rules, size(rhs) == 2|size(lhs) == 2)
rules_3_items <- subset(dota_rules, size(items) == 3)

We can see the highest lift association rules containing 3 heroes in the below table

inspect(rules_3_items[1:10])

The below graph shows these interactions, with nodes sized by support and coloured by lift

It can be difficult to differentiate interactions that involve 3 or more items in total from an increased effect of already known synergies (the combination of 2 existing synergies), or newly significant effects only achieved at a 3 item level.
This is one of the difficulties in interpreting item basket analysis.

In an example ofitem basket analysis on groceries, consider the following 2 potential cases: case 1:
if there were a rule saying yoghurt ==> berries and yoghurt ==> nuts, it may be the case that there is also an interaciton yoghurt ==> berries & nuts.
case 2: If instead consumers very rarely purchase more than one addition with yoghurt - they would either buy yoghurt and berries or yoghurt and nuts, a 3 item rule woud not exist.

The same logic can be applied to DOTA heroes. Taking Huskar as an example, there are very strong association rules between Huskar and Dazzle, and moderately strong association rules between Huskar and Omniknight. However it is unlikely that there is a strong 3 item association rule between these heroes, since both Dazzle and Omniknight are generally considered “support heroes”, performing a similar role in a game, and as such, are unlikely to appear on the same team.

Association rules with Omniknight are in the below table, as items 5 and 6 of Huskar’s association rules

# finding subsets of rules containing Huskar
huskar_rules <- subset(dota_rules, items %in% "Huskar")
inspect(huskar_rules)

However in the next table showing Huskar’s association rules involving 3 or more items, Omniknight is not present

# finding subsets of rules of 3 or more items containing Huskar
huskar_rules_3_items <- subset(rules_3_items, items %in% "Huskar")
inspect(huskar_rules_3_items)

Explaining Specific 3 Hero Association Rules

The below items show individual directional 3 hero interactions, either caused by a enhanced combination of a known 2 hero interation, or a new interaction.

The Dazzle-Slardar-ShadowFiend interaction below is likely due to all 3 heroes reducing enemy armour. In DOTA, armour debuffs increase hero damage exponentially rather than proportionally, therefore a 3 hero interaction is to be expected.

The Dazzle-Huskar-Slardar interaction, unlike the Dazzle-Huskar-Omniknight interaction previously discussed, is likely to be feasible here due to the 3 heroes occupying different roles, rather than sharing 1 role such as hard-support as before. The cause of the third level interaction is unknown, though a higher rater player may be able to understand a synergy between these heroes.

Note on Data Interpretation

Since the Data was obtained from 50,000 matches, which is only a moderately sized Database, there is the risk of vulnerability to noise. As an example, some players queue for games in parties of 2 or more, and some players favour picking from a very limited hero pool, or even the same hero many games in a row (a practice known as “spamming”).
The following 3 item association rule may be the result of a perceived synergy between the 3 heroes, generated from a number of random matches, or it may be an anomolous result of 3 people queuing for games together and picking their preferred hero each time.

Continuing with the example of Windranger, Omniknight and Phantom Asassin, a support of 0.001130792 implies 113 teams in which the three heroes appear together, which is a low enough value to be influenced by individual party members spamming heroes without thought of any perceived association rules.

wr_rules <- subset(rules_3_items, items %in% "Windranger")
inspect(wr_rules)
# There are only 113 teams out of 99,930 which contain this combination of heroes
print(0.001130792 * 99930)
[1] 113
